[Event "Fischer's Weapon Against the Najdorf: The Sozin Attack"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2024.12.18"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B90"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42104399"]

1. e4 { Greetings, and welcome to my course.

I am GM Sahaj Grover. I have written three courses for Chessable in the past, these are:

  *  Timeless Technique: Strategic Endgames [https://www.chessable.com/timeless-technique-strategic-endgames/course/42898/] alongside my good friend FM Daniel Barrish,

  *  The Cheeky Chigorin [https://www.chessable.com/the-cheeky-chigorin/course/88610/] with GM Abhijeet Gupta

  *  and most recently I wrote LTR: Sahaj and Srinath's London System [https://www.chessable.com/lifetime-repertoires-sahaj-and-srinaths-london-system/course/126261/] with GM N. Srinath.

Besides writing courses, I also like to play a bit: I have won World U-10 Championship in 2005, Bronze medal in World Junior Championship in 2011. After attaining the Grandmaster title, I briefly diverted my focus to explore diverse pursuits before returning to chess wholeheartedly following the completion of my studies.

Notably, I had the privilege of providing commentary for Chess.com during the prestigious Candidates Chess Tournament. This course is pretty special to me. Firstly this is my first solo project, but more importantly, this opening is extremely dear to me. I have played the Sozin my whole life. In the database, I have about 60 games (not including online chess) ranging from 2005 to 2024! I am pretty sure I would have more, but unfortunately, I lost all my games before 2005.

The idea for this course came to me in 2022, while preparing for a match against my country mate GM SP Sethuraman, who is also a prominent Chessable author. While preparing against him, I found an entirely new approach towards the Sozin that I had never analyzed before. I was quite excited as it does not happen frequently that something so fresh becomes viable over the board.

I did manage to play it against him, and got a good position too - but one blunder cost me the game. However, the idea was quite appealing to me. In fact, that same week - I emailed Maaike to ask her if anyone is covering this opening - if not, I would like to take it on. It did take much longer than expected, but I am happy with the final result. Let's dig in. } c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. Bc4 { The Sozin Attack. A longtime favourite of Bobby Fischer and many other legendary players. Once considered to be the most dangerous weapon against the Najdorf, this variation lost it's popularity over time. There are many players who play the Najdorf as their main weapon and have never faced the Sozin in their entire chess career! So, why choose the Sozin?

Firstly, in this day and age, pretty much everything we analyze is equal since strong engines are accessible to almost everyone. Therefore, I believe that the Sozin's decline in popularity over the past decade(s) makes a great surprise weapon that is packed with fresh ideas that are extremely dynamic where you can catch your opponent in a theoretical battle. } ( { Secondly, the Sozin limits Black's choices. In the majority of options against Najdorf, for example: } 6.Be3 { , } ) ( 6.Be2 { , or even the trending } ) ( 6.Rg1 { Black has the option of playing both, } 6...e5 { or } ( 6...e6 { . However, against the Sozin, ` rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 6 '  6...e6 is almost a guarantee where the chances of your preparation landing on the board are significantly high. } ) ) { Lastly, the line I have recommended is relatively new to most players where the variations are attacking in nature and quite dangerous to someone who has not prepared for it in advance. } e6 ( 6...g6 { is the Dragadorf Variation and is the main topic of this chapter. [/course/262406/0] } 7.f3 Bg7 8.Be3 Nbd7 9.Qd2 { Inside the chapter, we largely deal with ...h5 setups where Black delays castling. } ) ( 6...b5 { is addressed in the sidelines chapter. [/course/262406/2] I don't find it to be appealing and it is possible to transpose with } 7.Bb3 { , but I have given } ( 7.Bd5 { as an additional variation to try.

A) ` rnbqkb1r/4pppp/p2p1n2/1p6/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq b6 0 7 '  7.Bb3 e6 8.Be3 transposes to the main lines, the first chapter [/course/262406/4] and the Early ...Qc7 [/course/262406/5] chapter. } ( { B) } 7.Bd5 { . } ) ) ) 
7. Be3 Be7 { This is the mainline addressed in the first chapter. [/course/262406/5] } ( 7...Nc6 { The Najdorf-Classical Hybrid. [/course/262406/3] I am aware that this is a course on Najdorf. Still, the transposition towards the Classical is possible and I aimed to provide you with a repertoire that covers everything after ` rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6 '  6.Bc4 .

` r1bqkb1r/1p3ppp/p1nppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 2 8 '  8.Bb3 And here we discuss three options:

A) 8...Be7

B) 8...Qc7 and

C) 8...Na5 .

For more details, you can check out the chapter, but for the introduction purposes, I would like to show an example of a new idea that has not been tried out before. This can be seen after 8...Be7 9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.g4 There are about 10 games in the database on this position. For context, after 8...Be7 there are about 2,000. } ) ( 7...Qc7 { This is the main focus of the Early ...Qc7. [/course/262406/4] The point is to include ...Qc7-Bb3 and go with the same idea as in the main line [/course/262406/5], and to understand the differences that arise after this inclusion. } 8.Bb3 Nbd7 9.f3 { The idea is to launch g4 in the next move. The arising positions here almost entirely new and packed with attacking ideas. } ) 
8. Bb3 b5 
9. a3 O-O 
10. f3 { And once again our goal is to launch the kingside attack with g4-g5. I think it is important to mention that the bishop on b3 serves as a perfect piece that defends against any queenside attacking ideas as well as an attacker itself where the threat of g5-g6 becomes even greater due to it's control over the e6-square.

Furthermore, having the bishop on b3 also allows for fancy tactics like Nxe6 or Bxe6 in many scenarios, not to mention the simple Nd5! which is also shown throughout the course.

I believe this setup is quite dangerous for Black if they are underprepared, and to be frank, I think even with preparation - it is quite hard to remember everything from Black's side.

I hope you will enjoy this course, as much as I did making it. Good luck! See you on the other side. } *

