A) } 7...Nbd7? ) ( 7.Be3 { B) } 7...Qc7 ) ( 7.Be3 { C) } 7...Nc6 ) ( 7.Be3 { D) } 7...b5 ) ( 7.Be3 { E) } 7...Be7 ) ( 7.Be3 { - With A) } 7...Nbd7? { Black falls into our trap since we don't need to retreat Bb3 anymore and can simply play } 8.O-O { and after } 8...Nc5 9.f3! { where the threat of pushing b2-b4 is a major problem for Black. } ) ( 7.Be3 { - B) } 7...Qc7 { is the second choice. We will be retreating with } 8.Bb3 { where the position has more or less transposed into the mainstream theory with one key difference: Black's queen is now on c7. This can be a benefit in many lines, specifically where Black tries to go for ...Nbd7-Nc5-Nxb3 and force cxb3. The queen on c7 would almost always end up losing a tempo when the c-file opens up and White goes Rc1, aiming an x-ray. } ) ( 7.Be3 { - C) } 7...Nc6 { is the third choice. This was one of my major practical problems to tackle since my surprise weapon I had initially intended does not work in this situation, but it does transpose in majority of the lines. We will respond with } 8.Bb3 { with the intention of going 9.Nxc6 in the next move followed by 10.g4! @@StartSquare@@For reference, the line I wanted to go for was ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 7 '  7.Bb3 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.g4⁉ @@EndSquare@@ } { - D & E) ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...b5 / 7...Be7 . I have combined these two alternatives as they largely transpose into one another in the next move. After 7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 we will be going for 9.f3⁉ with the aim to launch a kingside attack via g4-g5-h4. We will discuss this in detail soon. } ) Be7 
8. Bb3 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gd1e2,Ge1c1,Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Ga2a3][%csl Ga3,Ge2,Gf3,Gg5,Gh4]} { Once this move is played - we should understand that our next few moves are going to be 'hand moves' since our setup is not going to change much in the majority of the cases. But let's try to understand it anyways. There are three different ways for Black to continue. } ( 8.Bb3 { A) } 8...O-O { we will go for the direct } 9.g4! { with the idea of launching an immediate kingside attack with g5-h4. Black must be extremely precise to not land in trouble here. } ) ( 8.Bb3 { B) } 8...Nc6 9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.g4! { is pretty standard and something seen in the Najdorf-Classical Hybrid [/variation/42303598/#/10/w] chapter. } ) ( 8.Bb3 { C) } 8...b5 { is the most important one. The setup we are aiming for looks something like this: f3-a3-Qe2-O-O-O-g4-g5-h4. It is also important to understand which moves to play at certain times. } ) {

  * Generally speaking, you should answer ...b5 with a3. This is because Black is able to achieve counterplay with ...b4 in some lines where our knight on a4 is going to be misplaced.

  * Furthermore, you have a choice between f3 and Qe2 and these moves are interchangeable.

  * Finally, and this is something I have addressed a couple of times already - when you castle on the queenside you should be mindful of ...Rxc3 sacrifice, especially because we have played a3 already. } b5 
9. a3 {[%cal Rb5b4][%csl Rb4]} { Preventing ...b4 ideas. Pushing a3 makes ...Rxc3 a more dangerous threat. However, it is simply not possible to castle on the longside without it. } ( 9.f3 O-O 10.Qe2 Qc7 11.O-O-O $6 { allows } 11...b4! { where } 12.Na4 Nbd7! { blocks the knight on a4. And now Black easily gets counterplay with ...Nc5 and ...Bd7. } ) O-O 
10. f3 {[%csl Ge4]} { Solidifying our position in the center and preparing for a g2-g4 launch soon. } ( 10.Qe2 $5 { This is also possible - and you can switch around between these two moves.

The benefit of playing Qe2 is that you might not need to play f3 and can save time by just going g4 straight. On the other hand, the benefit of starting with f3 is that you keep the option of going g4-g5 straight away without having to worry about the e4-pawn.

However, in most cases - these two will transpose and it comes down to what you are most comfortable with. } ) Bb7 
11. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1c1][%csl Gc1]} { Preparing to castle on the queenside. } Nc6 { The second most popular variation. There is a model game in this variation between Wesley So vs Abhimanyu Mishra played in 2023 where White won. We will closely follow this game. } 
12. O-O-O Na5 
13. g4 Rc8 ( 13...Nd7 { Will transpose after } 14.h4 Rc8 15.Kb1 { With a direct transposition. } ) 
14. Kb1! {[%mdl 32768]} { The evergreen move. This is perhaps the only time we are inviting the ...Rxc3 sacrifice. } Nd7 
15. h4 { The march continues. } Rxc3 { Finally. } 
16. bxc3 Nb6 {[%cal Ga5c4][%csl Gc4]} { Black prepares to pounce on the c4-square. } 
17. h5 Nac4 
18. Bxc4 Nxc4 
19. Bc1 ( 19.Bc1 { Protecting the a3-pawn. In the game between Wesley So vs Abhimanyu Mishra, Black made an error with } 19...d5 { which gave White a winning advantage. } { My understanding is that Abhimanyu analyzed this position without the 18.Bxc4 Nxc4 exchange and analyzed ` 3q1rk1/1b2bppp/pn1pp3/1p5P/2nNP1P1/PBP1BP2/2P1Q3/1K1R3R w - - 1 18 '  18.Bc1 immediately where 18...d5 is a pretty strong move. This goes to show that even one slight overlook can be fatal for Black. } ) Qa5 { Bringing the queen into play. } 
20. h6 {[%csl Rg7]} { We will fix our pawn on } { h6 for long-term attacking purposes. The lines are really crazy after { 20...g6 or 20...g5 , as you can check in the main chapter. [/variation/42449493/#/20/w] } *

[Event "Fischer's Weapon Against the Najdorf: The Sozin Attack"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Early Qc7 #1"]
[Date "2024.12.18"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B90"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/46823125"]

1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. Bc4 e6 ( 6...Nc6 $6 { falls into a nasty tactic. } 7.Nxc6! bxc6 8.e5! Nd7 { Black's only move since taking } ( 8...dxe5 { would allow } 9.Bxf7+ { . ` r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p1pp4/4P3/2B5/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 9 '  9.exd6 exd6 10.Qe2+ Be7 11.Bg5⩲ Followed by O-O-O. White's lead in development and Black's weak pawn on d6 should provide a comfortable game ahead. } ) ) 
7. Be3 ( { As I have mentioned, initially, } 7.Bb3 { was my main choice. However, the variation after } 7...Nbd7 8.Be3 Nc5 9.f3 Be7 { proved to be challenging. In particular, I disliked the variations where Black goes for ...h5 setups. Let me be clear - I don't think White has problems, but I decided to change my direction since ...Nbd7 is one of the most popular lines and currently the most trending. } ) ( { With } 7.Be3 { , I found the 'practical' problems were less common, and this is why I chose to change my move order. Comparative to 7.Bb3, this is far less common so the element of surprise works in our favour. } 7...Qc7 { will be the topic of this chapter. } ) ( 7.Be3 7...Nc6 { is covered in the Najdorf-Classical Hybrid chapter. [/course/262406/3] } ) ( 7.Be3 { With } 7...Nbd7? { Black falls into our trap since we don't need to retreat with Bb3 anymore and can simply play } 8.O-O { and after } 8...Nc5 9.f3! { where the threat of pushing b2-b4 is a major problem for Black, as seen [/variation/42449663/#/9/w] in the previous chapter. } ) ( 7.Be3 7...b5 { and } ( 7...Be7 { largely transpose into one another and were also covered in the first chapter. [/course/262406/5] } ) ) Qc7 ( 7...Qc7 { A pretty interesting yet rare try. Black's main idea behind this move is to play } 8.Bb3 Nbd7 $5 { on the next move. There are other alternatives too, but this seems to be the main one. } ) ( { We already [/variation/46814867/#/7/b] know that } 7...Nbd7 $6 { immediately falls into } 8.O-O Qc7 9.Bxe6! { since White did not waste a tempo retreating the bishop to b3. Hence, Black switches the move order to solve this issue. } { I would like to draw comparison between this and the Sozin mainline with ` rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6 '  6.Bc4 e6 7.Bb3 Nbd7 where the difference is the moves Be3 and ...Qc7 are yet to be played, but the transposition is possible regardless. That being said, I think that after 8.Be3 Black does not need to play 8...Qc7 immediately and can time it better.

This is one of the reasons I prefer this move order as opposed to 7.Bb3 Nbd7 . The reason why I prefer the inclusion ...Qc7 is that it can be a liability since there are quite a number of lines where White will throw Nf5! and after ...exf5 there is a crucial tempo with Nd5! which attacks the queen.

Another benefit is that after Black opts for ...Nbd7-c5 and ...b5 we are often pushing a3. In those lines ...Nxb3 is slightly preferred since after cxb3 followed by Rc1 poses a threat along the c-file which forces the black queen to lose a tempo. } ) 
8. Bb3 {[%mdl 32768]} { Logical retreat. We can now start eyeing on the kingside to create an early attack. There is an important point to address here: throughout the course, I have tried to maintain a certain style or setup that helps us remember the moves better, but in this scenario - there is a difference that needs to be addressed. } { The difference between ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Qc7 8.Bb3 b5 and 7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 ( the other main line chapter [/variation/42468986/#/8/b]). } { - In the case where ...Qc7 is included, we will be going for f3 and g4 or g4 directly, delaying the a2-a3 push. } { - And with ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Be7 we will be pushing 9.a3. There are two reasons for this: }{ Firstly, when Black plays ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Qc7 8.Bb3 b5 9.f3 there is always an option of 9...Nc6 which allows us to go 10.Nxc6 Qxc6 11.a4! which saves a crucial tempo.

Secondly, after ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 9.a3 if Black chooses to play 9...Qc7 then there is no need to push f3 and you can simply launch 10.g4! immediately and once again, save time. That being said, I don't think the difference is really noticeable unless your opponent is booked, which I think is very unlikely since Najdorf players usually have much bigger fish to fry. } b5 
9. f3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5][%csl Gg5]} { Gearing up for a kingside launch. As mentioned earlier, there is no need to push a2-a3 here. } Be7 ( 9...Nc6? { Falls into our trap. } 10.Nxc6 Qxc6 11.a4! { and now after } 11...b4 { There is a nice tactic } 12.a5! $18 { Threatening Ba4. Black's pawn on b4 is isolated and becomes a major weakness. We should aim to put our knight or bishop on b6 to restrict Black's space and the defense over the b4-pawn. } ) 
10. g4 ( 10.g4 { Typical follow-up. Black now has only one move } 10...b4 { that keeps things level, although some preference to White as you will see soon. If Black goes for } ( 10...O-O { then after } 11.g5! { Black's knight is unable to go to d7 because of the 12.Bxe6 sacrifice. If the knight goes } 11...Ne8 { then it becomes extremely bad as it has no contribution to the position. We should be able to go h4-h5 quickly and break with g6 eventually. Perhaps, this is another reason why a3 was delayed. } ) ) O-O $6  { For example, can be answered with: } 
11. g5! Nfd7 
12. Bxe6! fxe6 
13. Nxe6 Qc4 
14. Nxf8 Bxf8 { The only move! } ( 14...Nxf8? { Allows a nice tempo with } 15.Nd5! { and after } 15...Bd8 16.Bb6! { Finishes the game sooner rather than later. Black's only real choice now is to capture } 16...Bxg5 17.h4! $18 { and now the bishop on g5 is out of squares. } ) 
15. Qd5+ Qxd5 
16. Nxd5 $14  { Gives White a comfortable advantage in the endgame. Both materially and also in terms of practical play. } *

