2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. Bc4 g6 { The infamous 'Dragadorf' variation. The Dragadorf is a hybrid setup of two theoretical giants: Dragon & Najdorf. This variation came into fashion in the early 2010s with a mission to divert mainstream theory and confuse players due to its unique approach toward opening theory. The setup looks weird at first, and that's the gimmick.

Logically speaking, we should assume that Black will not be going for the Dragon setup with ...Bg7; ...O-O; ...Nc6 since the move ...a6 is now a waste of a crucial tempo in an opening that has a reputation for being extremely sharp. We will focus on ...h5 setups instead where the position remains complex and largely unexplored. } 
7. f3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { I believe } 7.Be3 { is pretty similar and will transpose in the next move. } ) Bg7 ( 7...h5 { A bit too soon. White has not yet committed Be3 and can use this opportunity to place the bishop on a better square. } 8.Bg5 $5 Bg7 9.Qd2 $16 { This is an important moment to understand the difference between the Be3 and Bg5. We are simply not allowing Black to opt for the Dragadorf setup. For example, if Black plays } 9...b5 { , we can answer with } 10.Bd5! { and now taking } 10...Nxd5 { is not possible because after } 11.Nxd5 { the e7-pawn is left hanging. } ) 
8. Be3 Nbd7 $5  { This is where the confusion begins.

Black already deviates from the usual c6-square that isn't viable anymore. With the knight on d7, Black aims to create a setup with ...b5;...Bb7;...Rc8 while holding the king on e8 until the queenside fully develops.

To someone who faces this setup for the first time, it feels strange that Black on purpose is avoiding to castle, so the rational player would try to launch an assault on the king. This is partially wrong. I will elaborate on this a bit later. } 
9. Qd2 b5 
10. Bb3 h5 $5  { Although not the most popular, this move is the most challenging. Black's idea is to wait and see which side we will castle.

I spent quite a bit of time on this position and what I understand is that if White castles on the queenside, then it is better for Black's bishop to be on d7, and if White castles on the kingside, then Black can continue naturally with ...Bb7. } 
11. O-O { I like this move. The follow-up is to go for a4 breakthrough and create chances on the queenside. I will explain this further in an informational [/variation/42104487/#/11/w]. } Bb7 { The clickable shows why it is important to guard the c6-square. But our follow-up remains the same. } ( 11...O-O? { allows for } 12.a4 { and after } 12...bxa4 13.Nc6! { A cute intermezzo. Black is forced to play } 13...Qe8 { to not lose a pawn and now White can capture with } 14.Bxa4 $18 { Followed by e5 next. } ) 
12. a4 b4 { Is also possible. } 
13. Na2 {[%csl Rb4]} e5 ( 13...a5 14.c3! bxc3 15.Nxc3 { White maintains a comfortable edge because of the outpost on b5 which restricts any counterplay. The follow-up can be Ndb5; Rad1. } ) 
14. Ne2 a5 
15. c3 Nc5 {[%csl Rb3]} { A computer-ish move. } 
16. Nec1! {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,Rb4]} { We need the knight on a2 to keep the pressure on b4. } Ba6 
17. Rd1 bxc3 
18. Nxc3 {[%csl Rd6]} Nxb3 
19. Nxb3 Bc4 
20. Nc1 $14  {[%csl Rd6]} { And we will take the pawn on d6 next. } *

