C) } ) ( 8...Na5 { . } ) ) ( 8.Bb3 { A) } 8...Be7 { is the most popular answer here. We will go for a fairly new approach with } 9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.g4 { with ideas of Be3, g5, Qd2, h4 and eventually O-O-O. Once again we see the importance of the Sozin bishop who plays a vital defensive role on the queenside. } ) ( 8.Bb3 { B) } 8...Qc7 { is the second most popular move. We will once again go for the rare } 9.Nxc6 Qxc6 { ( 9...bxc6 would result in a similar position after ` r1b1kb1r/1pq2ppp/p1nppn2/8/3NP3/1BN1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 4 9 '  9.g4 and I fail to see the benefit of having the queen on c7 as opposed to ...Be7) ` r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1qppn2/8/4P3/1BN1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 10 '  10.Qd3⁉ and now Black is simply not in time to develop his king because of threats like Ba4. We will analyse this a bit deeper in a trainable. [/variation/42324361/#/10/w] } ) ( 8.Bb3 { C) } 8...Na5 { is the third most popular move and perhaps the most challenging one since it avoids the entire idea of going Nxc6. Here I recommend } 9.f4 $5 { with ideas of going 10.g4 or 10.f5, in some cases White can also throw e4-e5 which can be quite dangerous. Black has to be precise here and play } 9...Qc7 10.f5 Nxb3 11.cxb3 { with ideas of Rc1 prove to be quite challenging for Black. } ) Na5 { Black's third most popular option, and it is the one computer prefers the most. I believe one of the main reasons is that it does not allow for the Nxc6-g4 plan. So, besides not allowing this - what is the main plan?

To understand this further, we need to draw some comparisons between having the knight on a5 and c5. In the 6.Bc4 e6 7.Be3 Qc7 [/course/262406/5] chapter, we can see the Black knight developing via ...Nbd7-Nc5. In that chapter our focus was largely to castle on the queenside, however, this is not as appealing anymore. I think the entire idea of f3-g4-g5 and castling on the queenside is less effective if Black's knight is placed on a5 as opposed to c5, this is largely because the c-file is left open and ...Rxc3 sacrifice in the future could become dangerous.

I should also mention that Black is not necessarily planning to go ...Nxb3 or ...Nc4 any time soon. Instead, the idea is to try and develop via ...b5-Be7-O-O-Bb7-Rc8 and only then consider going ...Nc4. So, timing is quite important here. I managed to find a line which poses many practical challenges to White and at the moment, quite underappreciated in modern theory. } 
9. f4! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Ge4e5,Yg2g4,Yg4g5]} { The main move. I see two ideas behind this move:

1) push e5 to break the center and

2) to try and create kingside attacking chances via g4-g5. } Qc7 { Most logical. Black develops the queen and prevents the e5-break. } 
10. g4 $5  ( { I absolutely love this move. Generally speaking, } 10.f5 { is the most popular here but after } 10...Nxb3 11.cxb3 b5! { I could not find a line that seemed appealing - there are quite a number of lines where Black has to be precise, though. That being said, I think this move is much better in practical play since your opponent will most likely be out of theory at this point and if they have not memorised this move, I think it is next to impossible to survive here for Black. } ) d5 { The most challenging move, with only one game in the database... from 1973... which Black lost. } 
11. e5 Nd7 
12. Qf3 ( 12.Qf3 { In the aforementioned game, White opted for 12.O-O instead. Therefore, this is a novelty. Our idea here is to delay Black's queenside development via ...b5-Bb7 since after } 12...b5 { there is } 13.Bxd5! exd5 14.Nxd5 Qb7 { and now simply } 15.O-O-O { followed by } { 16.e6! seems lethal. } ) Bb4! { Only move. From this point onwards, we will be seeing a lot of those from Black's side. } 
13. O-O! { King safety first. } Nb6! {[%cal Gb6c4,Ga5c4][%csl Gc4]} { Black's intentions are clear - to play ...Nbc4/Nac4 as soon as possible and to be able to recapture with the knight. } 
14. Nce2 ( { I think } 14.Rad1 $5 $13 { deserves attention as well - but I find the main move to be far more logical. } ) Nbc4! { Important move since the other knight belongs on c6. I think this move is particularly not the easiest to play :) } ( 14...Nac4 $6 15.Bc1! $14 { And now the b6-knight is not ideally placed. We can just kick the bishop with c3 followed by Bc2. } ) 
15. Bc1 Nc6 
16. c3 Nxd4 
17. Nxd4 Bc5 
18. Bd1 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1e3]} ( { The plan is simple: push b3 and develop the bishop via Be3. Note that keeping the light-squared bishop on d1 is better than c2 since after } 18.Bc2 Bd7 19.b3 { Black can play } 19...Na3 $5 { which gains a tempo. I continue the analysis in the main chapter. [/variation/42298953/#/18/w] } ) *

[Event "Fischer's Weapon Against the Najdorf: The Sozin Attack"]
[White "1) Main Line: 7...b5 & 7...Be7"]
[Black "7...Nbd7 #1"]
[Date "2024.12.18"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B90"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/42484634"]

1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. Bc4 e6 ( 6...Nc6 $6 { falls into a nasty tactic. } 7.Nxc6! bxc6 8.e5! Nd7 { Black's only move since taking } ( 8...dxe5 { would allow } 9.Bxf7+ { . ` r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p1pp4/4P3/2B5/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 9 '  9.exd6 exd6 10.Qe2+ Be7 11.Bg5⩲ Followed by O-O-O. White's lead in development and Black's weak pawn on d6 should provide a comfortable game ahead. } ) ) 
7. Be3 ( { Initially, } 7.Bb3 { was my main choice. However, the variation after } 7...Nbd7 8.Be3 Nc5 9.f3 Be7 { proved to be challenging. In particular, I disliked the variations where Black goes for ...h5 setups. Let me be clear - I don't think White has problems, but I decided to change my direction since ...Nbd7 is one of the most popular lines and currently the most trending. } ) ( { With } 7.Be3 { - I found the 'practical' problems were less common, and this is why I chose to change my move order. Let's dive into 7.Be3 . Comparative to 7.Bb3, this is far less common so the element of surprise works in our favour. Black's choices are:

A) } 7...Nbd7? ) ( 7.Be3 { B) } 7...Qc7 ) ( 7.Be3 { C) } 7...Nc6 ) ( 7.Be3 { D) } 7...b5 ) ( 7.Be3 { E) } 7...Be7 ) ( 7.Be3 { - With A) } 7...Nbd7? { Black falls into our trap since we don't need to retreat Bb3 anymore and can simply play } 8.O-O { and after } 8...Nc5 9.f3! { where the threat of pushing b2-b4 is a major problem for Black. } ) ( 7.Be3 { - B) } 7...Qc7 { is the second choice. We will be retreating with } 8.Bb3 { where the position has more or less transposed into the mainstream theory with one key difference: Black's queen is now on c7. This can be a benefit in many lines, specifically where Black tries to go for ...Nbd7-Nc5-Nxb3 and force cxb3. The queen on c7 would almost always end up losing a tempo when the c-file opens up and White goes Rc1, aiming an x-ray. } ) ( 7.Be3 { - C) } 7...Nc6 { is the third choice. This was one of my major practical problems to tackle since my surprise weapon I had initially intended does not work in this situation, but it does transpose in majority of the lines. We will respond with } 8.Bb3 { with the intention of going 9.Nxc6 in the next move followed by 10.g4! @@StartSquare@@For reference, the line I wanted to go for was ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 7 '  7.Bb3 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.g4⁉ @@EndSquare@@ } { - D & E) ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...b5 / 7...Be7 . I have combined these two alternatives as they largely transpose into one another in the next move. After 7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 we will be going for 9.f3⁉ with the aim to launch a kingside attack via g4-g5-h4. We will discuss this in detail soon. } ) Nbd7 $6  { This is one of the major reasons for choosing our previous move. } 
8. O-O! { We can leave the bishop on c4 for now. } Qc7 ( { Meets the same fate as } 8...b5 { . } ) 
9. Bxe6! fxe6 
10. Nxe6 Qb8 { Only move. There is a similar idea mentioned as a clickable/alternative from another variation [/variation/42324405/#/9/w/1.3] where ...Qb8 is also the only move. This is probably because the threat of Nc7+ needs to be stopped and the queen on any other square such as c6 or c4 can be kicked. } 
11. Nd5 Nxd5 
12. exd5 Nf6 
13. Re1 { There are other options too, but this one seems cleanest. } Bxe6 
14. Bg5 {[%cal Re1e8][%csl Re8]} Be7 
15. Rxe6 ( 15.Rxe6 { With a good position. The domination of the e-file is far too powerful. Black pretty much has to play } 15...Rf8 16.Bxf6 Rxf6 17.Qh5+ Rf7 18.Qxh7 Kd7 19.Qh3 { , which gives White three pawns for the piece and some counterplay in the form of active pieces. } ) *

