2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. Bc4 e6 ( 6...Nc6 $6 { falls into a nasty tactic. } 7.Nxc6! bxc6 8.e5! Nd7 { Black's only move since taking } ( 8...dxe5 { would allow } 9.Bxf7+ { . ` r1bqkb1r/3npppp/p1pp4/4P3/2B5/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 1 9 '  9.exd6 exd6 10.Qe2+ Be7 11.Bg5⩲ Followed by O-O-O. White's lead in development and Black's weak pawn on d6 should provide a comfortable game ahead. } ) ) 
7. Be3 ( { Initially, } 7.Bb3 { was my main choice. However, the variation after } 7...Nbd7 8.Be3 Nc5 9.f3 Be7 { proved to be challenging. In particular, I disliked the variations where Black goes for ...h5 setups. Let me be clear - I don't think White has problems, but I decided to change my direction since ...Nbd7 is one of the most popular lines and currently the most trending. } ) ( { With } 7.Be3 { - I found the 'practical' problems were less common, and this is why I chose to change my move order. Let's dive into 7.Be3 . Comparative to 7.Bb3, this is far less common so the element of surprise works in our favour. Black's choices are:

A) } 7...Nbd7? ) ( 7.Be3 { B) } 7...Qc7 ) ( 7.Be3 { C) } 7...Nc6 ) ( 7.Be3 { D) } 7...b5 ) ( 7.Be3 { E) } 7...Be7 ) ( 7.Be3 { - With A) } 7...Nbd7? { Black falls into our trap since we don't need to retreat Bb3 anymore and can simply play } 8.O-O { and after } 8...Nc5 9.f3! { where the threat of pushing b2-b4 is a major problem for Black. } ) ( 7.Be3 { - B) } 7...Qc7 { is the second choice. We will be retreating with } 8.Bb3 { where the position has more or less transposed into the mainstream theory with one key difference: Black's queen is now on c7. This can be a benefit in many lines, specifically where Black tries to go for ...Nbd7-Nc5-Nxb3 and force cxb3. The queen on c7 would almost always end up losing a tempo when the c-file opens up and White goes Rc1, aiming an x-ray. } ) ( 7.Be3 { - C) } 7...Nc6 { is the third choice. This was one of my major practical problems to tackle since my surprise weapon I had initially intended does not work in this situation, but it does transpose in majority of the lines. We will respond with } 8.Bb3 { with the intention of going 9.Nxc6 in the next move followed by 10.g4! @@StartSquare@@For reference, the line I wanted to go for was ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 7 '  7.Bb3 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.g4⁉ @@EndSquare@@ } { - D & E) ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...b5 / 7...Be7 . I have combined these two alternatives as they largely transpose into one another in the next move. After 7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 we will be going for 9.f3⁉ with the aim to launch a kingside attack via g4-g5-h4. We will discuss this in detail soon. } ) Be7 
8. Bb3 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gd1e2,Ge1c1,Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Ga2a3][%csl Ga3,Ge2,Gf3,Gg5,Gh4]} { Once this move is played - we should understand that our next few moves are going to be 'hand moves' since our setup is not going to change much in the majority of the cases. But let's try to understand it anyways. There are three different ways for Black to continue. } ( 8.Bb3 { A) } 8...O-O { we will go for the direct } 9.g4! { with the idea of launching an immediate kingside attack with g5-h4. Black must be extremely precise to not land in trouble here. } ) ( 8.Bb3 { B) } 8...Nc6 9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.g4! { is pretty standard and something seen in the Najdorf-Classical Hybrid [/variation/42303598/#/10/w] chapter. } ) ( 8.Bb3 { C) } 8...b5 { is the most important one. The setup we are aiming for looks something like this: f3-a3-Qe2-O-O-O-g4-g5-h4. It is also important to understand which moves to play at certain times. } ) {

  * Generally speaking, you should answer ...b5 with a3. This is because Black is able to achieve counterplay with ...b4 in some lines where our knight on a4 is going to be misplaced.

  * Furthermore, you have a choice between f3 and Qe2 and these moves are interchangeable.

  * Finally, and this is something I have addressed a couple of times already - when you castle on the queenside you should be mindful of ...Rxc3 sacrifice, especially because we have played a3 already. } b5 
9. a3 {[%cal Rb5b4][%csl Rb4]} { Preventing ...b4 ideas. We already know that pushing a3 makes ...Rxc3 a more dangerous threat. However, it is simply not possible to castle on the longside without it. } ( 9.f3 O-O 10.Qe2 Qc7 11.O-O-O $6 { Allows } 11...b4! { Where after } 12.Na4 Nbd7! { Blocks the knight on a4. And now Black easily gets counterplay with ...Nc5 and Bd7. } ) Qc7 { This will seem familiar. We arrive at a similar position as in the 7.Be3 Qc7 chapter [/variation/42324365/#/9/w] with one difference: we have played f2-f3 instead of a2-a3.

The difference between these two moves has little impact on the overall position. As mentioned earlier, one drawback of pushing a2-a3 is that Black has the ...Rxc3 sacrifice, which is now blocked by the queen. On the other hand, no one is stopping us from pushing g2-g4 without f2-f3 and this move would only be played once Black commits ...Bb7 in order to protect the e4-pawn. } 
10. g4 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gg4g5][%csl Gg5]} { Let's begin. This is also a perfect example to demonstrate why there is no need to push f2-f3 anymore. In many cases, we can just push g5 and just push f4 straight away. } Nc6? { Careless. We can now gain material by force. } 
11. g5! Nd7 
12. Bxe6 $18  { We have seen this story a few times already, and we will see it again :) } *

