8. Bb3 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gd1e2,Ge1c1,Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Ga2a3][%csl Ga3,Ge2,Gf3,Gg5,Gh4]} { Once this move is played - we should understand that our next few moves are going to be 'hand moves' since our setup is not going to change much in the majority of the cases. But let's try to understand it anyways. There are three different ways for Black to continue. } ( 8.Bb3 { A) } 8...O-O { we will go for the direct } 9.g4! { with the idea of launching an immediate kingside attack with g5-h4. Black must be extremely precise to not land in trouble here. } ) ( 8.Bb3 { B) } 8...Nc6 9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.g4! { is pretty standard and something seen in the Najdorf-Classical Hybrid [/variation/42303598/#/10/w] chapter. } ) ( 8.Bb3 { C) } 8...b5 { is the most important one. The setup we are aiming for looks something like this: f3-a3-Qe2-O-O-O-g4-g5-h4. It is also important to understand which moves to play at certain times. } ) {

  * Generally speaking, you should answer ...b5 with a3. This is because Black is able to achieve counterplay with ...b4 in some lines where our knight on a4 is going to be misplaced.

  * Furthermore, you have a choice between f3 and Qe2 and these moves are interchangeable.

  * Finally, and this is something I have addressed a couple of times already - when you castle on the queenside you should be mindful of ...Rxc3 sacrifice, especially because we have played a3 already. } b5 
9. a3 {[%cal Rb5b4][%csl Rb4]} { Preventing ...b4 ideas. We already know that pushing a3 makes ...Rxc3 a more dangerous threat. However, it is simply not possible to castle on the longside without it. } ( 9.f3 O-O 10.Qe2 Qc7 11.O-O-O $6 { Allows } 11...b4! { Where after } 12.Na4 Nbd7! { Blocks the knight on a4. And now Black easily gets counterplay with ...Nc5 and Bd7. } ) O-O 
10. f3 {[%csl Ge4]} { Solidifying our position in the center and preparing for a g2-g4 launch soon. } ( 10.Qe2 $5 { This is also possible - and you can switch around between these two moves.

The benefit of playing Qe2 is that you might not need to play f3 and can save time by just going g4 straight. On the other hand, the benefit of starting with f3 is that you keep the option of going g4-g5 straight away without having to worry about the e4-pawn.

However, in most cases - these two will transpose and it comes down to what you are most comfortable with. } ) Bb7 
11. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1c1][%csl Gc1]} { Preparing to castle on the queenside. } Nc6 { The second most popular variation. There is a model game in this variation between Wesley So vs Abhimanyu Mishra played in 2023 where White won. We will closely follow this game. } 
12. O-O-O b4 $5  { This was tried recently between Ivic,V vs Brkic,A in 2024. } 
13. Nxc6 {[%mdl 32768]} Bxc6 
14. axb4 Qb8! ( { Without this move, ...b4 does not work. For example, if Black goes } 14...Rb8 { then } 15.e5 { would be deadly. } ) 
15. Rd4 {[%csl Gb4]} { Defending the pawn. } Ne8 {[%cal Ge7f6][%csl Rd4]} { Opening the f6 square for the e7-bishop. } 
16. Rhd1 Bf6 
17. Rc4 {[%csl Rc6]} Qb7 {[%csl Gc6]} { Black once again threatens to annoy the rook with ...Bb5. } 
18. Qd2 { Getting away from the pin. } Bb5 
19. Rd4 Bxd4 
20. Qxd4 ( { In the aforementioned game, White went for } 20.Bxd4 { - I think this capture is slightly stronger. } ) a5 { Opening up the queenside. } 
21. e5! {[%csl Rd6,Re8,Rf6]} { Bringing the attention back to the center. This move is quite strong especially when Black's knight is misplaced on e8. } axb4 ( 21...dxe5? 22.Qxe5 Bd7 23.b5 $18 { Neutralised any queenside play. There are quite a number of threats here such as Bd4, Ne4, Bc5 etc. } ) 
22. Qxb4 Ra1+ 
23. Kd2 Rxd1+ 
24. Nxd1 ( 24.Nxd1 { The pawn on e5 still remains a power house. Black is unable to go } 24...dxe5 { because of } 25.Bc5! ) Qd7 { Getting away from the pin. } 
25. c4 Bc6 
26. Kc2 Qe7 
27. Nc3 { The endgame remains equal - but I feel that White can still push on the queenside because of the b & c passers, especially if the queens get exchanged. } *

