7. Be3 ( { As I have mentioned, initially, } 7.Bb3 { was my main choice. However, the variation after } 7...Nbd7 8.Be3 Nc5 9.f3 Be7 { proved to be challenging. In particular, I disliked the variations where Black goes for ...h5 setups. Let me be clear - I don't think White has problems, but I decided to change my direction since ...Nbd7 is one of the most popular lines and currently the most trending. } ) ( { With } 7.Be3 { , I found the 'practical' problems were less common, and this is why I chose to change my move order. Comparative to 7.Bb3, this is far less common so the element of surprise works in our favour. } 7...Qc7 { will be the topic of this chapter. } ) ( 7.Be3 7...Nc6 { is covered in the Najdorf-Classical Hybrid chapter. [/course/262406/3] } ) ( 7.Be3 { With } 7...Nbd7? { Black falls into our trap since we don't need to retreat with Bb3 anymore and can simply play } 8.O-O { and after } 8...Nc5 9.f3! { where the threat of pushing b2-b4 is a major problem for Black, as seen [/variation/42449663/#/9/w] in the previous chapter. } ) ( 7.Be3 7...b5 { and } ( 7...Be7 { largely transpose into one another and were also covered in the first chapter. [/course/262406/5] } ) ) Qc7 ( 7...Qc7 { A pretty interesting yet rare try. Black's main idea behind this move is to play } 8.Bb3 Nbd7 $5 { on the next move. There are other alternatives too, but this seems to be the main one. } ) ( { We already [/variation/42484634/#/7/b] know that } 7...Nbd7 $6 { immediately falls into } 8.O-O Qc7 9.Bxe6! { since White did not waste a tempo retreating the bishop to b3. Hence, Black switches the move order to solve this issue. } { I would like to draw comparison between this and the Sozin mainline with ` rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6 '  6.Bc4 e6 7.Bb3 Nbd7 where the difference is the moves Be3 and ...Qc7 are yet to be played, but the transposition is possible regardless. That being said, I think that after 8.Be3 Black does not need to play 8...Qc7 immediately and can time it better.

This is one of the reasons I prefer this move order as opposed to 7.Bb3 Nbd7 . The reason why I prefer the inclusion ...Qc7 is that it can be a liability since there are quite a number of lines where White will throw Nf5! and after ...exf5 there is a crucial tempo with Nd5! which attacks the queen.

Another benefit is that after Black opts for ...Nbd7-c5 and ...b5 we are often pushing a3. In those lines ...Nxb3 is slightly preferred since after cxb3 followed by Rc1 poses a threat along the c-file which forces the black queen to lose a tempo. } ) 
8. Bb3 {[%mdl 32768]} { Logical retreat. We can now start eyeing on the kingside to create an early attack. There is an important point to address here: throughout the course, I have tried to maintain a certain style or setup that helps us remember the moves better, but in this scenario - there is a difference that needs to be addressed. } { The difference between ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Qc7 8.Bb3 b5 and 7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 ( the other main line chapter [/variation/42468986/#/8/b]). } { - In the case where ...Qc7 is included, we will be going for f3 and g4 or g4 directly, delaying the a2-a3 push. } { - And with ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Be7 we will be pushing 9.a3. There are two reasons for this: }{ Firstly, when Black plays ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Qc7 8.Bb3 b5 9.f3 there is always an option of 9...Nc6 which allows us to go 10.Nxc6 Qxc6 11.a4! which saves a crucial tempo.

Secondly, after ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 9.a3 if Black chooses to play 9...Qc7 then there is no need to push f3 and you can simply launch 10.g4! immediately and once again, save time. That being said, I don't think the difference is really noticeable unless your opponent is booked, which I think is very unlikely since Najdorf players usually have much bigger fish to fry. } Nc6 ( 8...Nc6 { This is another example of the Najdorf-Classical Hybrid system mentioned previously. However, the inclusion of ...Qc7 seems a bit unnecessary since we can still play } 9.Nxc6 { where Black is pretty much forced to capture with the pawn, which defeats the purpose of playing ...Qc7. } ) 
9. Nxc6! Qxc6 ( { Seems far more logical, as it justifies ...Qc7. However, Black is now in big trouble. } 9...bxc6 10.g4! { leads to a similar position as the Najdorf-Classical [/course/262406/3] chapter: ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 7 '  7.Be3 Nc6 8.Bb3 Be7 9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.g4! and once again the move ...Qc7 is quite unnecessary here. } ) 
10. Qd3! {[%cal Gb3a4,Ra4e8][%csl Ra4]} { Threatening Ba4 next. } b5 { The only other move. } ( 10...Bd7? { Would waste a lot of time for Black } 11.O-O-O b5 12.f4! { With the idea of 13. e5 next. And if Black goes for } 12...b4 { then } 13.Nd5! exd5 14.e5 $16 { Is simply crushing. } ) ( 10...Be7? { Allows for } 11.Ba4 b5 12.Nxb5 $16 { And White enjoys an extra pawn for no compensation. } ) 
11. a4! {[%csl Rb5]} { Loosening Black's grip over the a4-e8 diagonal. } b4 ( 11...Rb8? { Loses to } 12.axb5 axb5 13.Nxb5 $18 { And Black cannot capture back due to Ba4. } ) 
12. a5! {[%cal Gb3a4,Ra4e8][%csl Ga4,Rc6,Re8]} { Boom. An extremely important idea to remember as this is perhaps the main reason why the whole ...Qc7;...Nc6 plan does not work out well for Black. } Bd7 
13. Na4 Qxe4 ( 13...Qxe4 { Black has to capture the pawn as otehrwise we can play } 14.Nb6 { anyways and will get a similar position with an extra pawn. } ) 
14. Nb6 Qxd3 
15. cxd3 Rb8 
16. Bc4 $16  {[%csl Ra6]} ( 16.Bc4 { And we will capture the a6-pawn in the next move. White has a fantastic position - practically winning even. Black can play } 16...Be7 17.Bxa6 { and there is no rush to push the a-pawn at all. White can instead bring the h1-rook into play via Ke2; Rhc1 and so on. } ) *

