Firstly, in almost all cases we will answer to ...b5 with a3 in order to prevent ...b4 and place our bishop to a2. } ( 9.f3 { Secondly, and this is an extension to the first point: it is not recommended to play a3 without ...b5. For example, should Black play } 9...Nc5 { then } 10.a3 { would allow for } 10...Nxb3 11.cxb3 { and note that since the black pawn is on b7 it allows Black to answer Rc1 with ...Qb8. I have tried to avoid this position throughout the whole chapter. } ) { Thirdly, be on the lookout for sacrifices. In specific:

1) Bxe6,

2) Nf5 and

3) Nd5.

In many of the lines - this can be quite dangerous.

Fourthly, your queen's placement matters. In almost all cases if Black's knight is on c5 then Qd2 is better and if the knight is on e5 then Qe2 is better. I will explain this in further detail in a trainable.

Finally, please keep the ideal setup in mind. This is g4-g5, Qd2 or Qe2, O-O-O, a3, and Ba2. If we are able to achieve this, the setup is successful. } ( 9.Bxe6 $5 { From a practical point of view, I see this as an alternative, especially in faster formats. However, I could not justify this in front of a computer - hence, I have made it clickable. } 9...fxe6 10.Nxe6 { The reason is that Black now has to find } 10...Qb8! { , which I feel is not easy in an actual game. This move is the reason why I did not make Bxe6 an alternative. However, the arising line is still equal. } ( 10...Qa5 { Can be met with } 11.Nxf8! Nxf8 12.Qxd6 { White now has three pawns for a piece and a fantastic compensation. I feel that there is only one move that should be addressed here: } { Nxe4 $5 13.Qd5! Qxd5 14.Nxd5 Ne6 15.Nb6 Rb8 16.O-O-O⩲ And Black still has a lot of problems to solve. } ) ( 10...Qc6 11.Nd5! $16 { Seems horrible for Black. } ) ( 10...Qc4 { Is similar to 10...Qa5. } 11.Nxf8 Rxf8 12.Qxd6 Kf7 13.Bd4 $14 { With O-O-O to follow. White has more than enough compensation for the piece. } ) 11.Qd4 { Preparing to castle and attack the d6-pawn. } ( 11.f4 $5 { Can also be investigated further. } ) 11...Ne5 12.Nxf8 Rxf8 13.O-O-O $10 { And White will eventually take on d6 which will equalise matters. } { 11...Kf7? Lands in serious trouble once again. 12.Ng5+! Since 12...Kg8 is not possible because of 13.Qc4+ . } ) b5 
10. a3! {[%mdl 32768]} { Following the rule of thumb. @@StartBlockQuote@@ Black plays ...b5 try to push a3 and prevent ...b4 ideas.@@EndBlockQuote@@ } Rb8 
11. g4 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gd1e2,Yd7c5,Yd1d2][%csl Yc5,Yd2,Ge2,Ge5]} { This is a good example of how Black's knight on d7 affects your queen placement. The rule is: @@StartBlockQuote@@If 11...Nc5 then 12. Qd2 and if 11...Ne5 then 12. Qe2. @@EndBlockQuote@@I think it is important to understand why we do this.

• When Black puts the knight on c5, then the main plan revolves around pushing ...b4. This is why the queen is needed on d2 so we can counter with axb4-...Rxb4, g5-...Nd7, and Nd5. This discovered attack almost always stops ...b4 and Black will have to end up wasting a move with ...Qb7/Qb6 or prepare for ...a5; ...b4 ideas, which would waste a tempo. } ( 11.g4 { • If Black plays } 11...Ne5 { then the plan usually revolves around playing ...Nc4 instead since ...b4 is no longer dangerous as after axb4-Rxb4 the bishop on b3 is no longer under attack. White can probably even castle on the queenside without any major worries. This is why Qe2 is better since ...Nc4 would not threaten the queen anymore.

Secondly, when Black's knight is placed on e5 we can also create threats like f4⁉ and kicking away the knight and the queen on e2 would be useful in protecting the light squares like g4 and c4 where the knight can jump. } ) Nc5 
12. Qd2 { Transposes to the 9...Nc5 lines. [/variation/42324402/#/12/w] } *

