7. Be3 ( { As I have mentioned, initially, } 7.Bb3 { was my main choice. However, the variation after } 7...Nbd7 8.Be3 Nc5 9.f3 Be7 { proved to be challenging. In particular, I disliked the variations where Black goes for ...h5 setups. Let me be clear - I don't think White has problems, but I decided to change my direction since ...Nbd7 is one of the most popular lines and currently the most trending. } ) ( { With } 7.Be3 { , I found the 'practical' problems were less common, and this is why I chose to change my move order. Comparative to 7.Bb3, this is far less common so the element of surprise works in our favour. } 7...Qc7 { will be the topic of this chapter. } ) ( 7.Be3 7...Nc6 { is covered in the Najdorf-Classical Hybrid chapter. [/course/262406/3] } ) ( 7.Be3 { With } 7...Nbd7? { Black falls into our trap since we don't need to retreat with Bb3 anymore and can simply play } 8.O-O { and after } 8...Nc5 9.f3! { where the threat of pushing b2-b4 is a major problem for Black, as seen [/variation/42449663/#/9/w] in the previous chapter. } ) ( 7.Be3 7...b5 { and } ( 7...Be7 { largely transpose into one another and were also covered in the first chapter. [/course/262406/5] } ) ) Qc7 ( 7...Qc7 { A pretty interesting yet rare try. Black's main idea behind this move is to play } 8.Bb3 Nbd7 $5 { on the next move. There are other alternatives too, but this seems to be the main one. } ) ( { We already [/variation/42484634/#/7/b] know that } 7...Nbd7 $6 { immediately falls into } 8.O-O Qc7 9.Bxe6! { since White did not waste a tempo retreating the bishop to b3. Hence, Black switches the move order to solve this issue. } { I would like to draw comparison between this and the Sozin mainline with ` rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6 '  6.Bc4 e6 7.Bb3 Nbd7 where the difference is the moves Be3 and ...Qc7 are yet to be played, but the transposition is possible regardless. That being said, I think that after 8.Be3 Black does not need to play 8...Qc7 immediately and can time it better.

This is one of the reasons I prefer this move order as opposed to 7.Bb3 Nbd7 . The reason why I prefer the inclusion ...Qc7 is that it can be a liability since there are quite a number of lines where White will throw Nf5! and after ...exf5 there is a crucial tempo with Nd5! which attacks the queen.

Another benefit is that after Black opts for ...Nbd7-c5 and ...b5 we are often pushing a3. In those lines ...Nxb3 is slightly preferred since after cxb3 followed by Rc1 poses a threat along the c-file which forces the black queen to lose a tempo. } ) 
8. Bb3 { Logical retreat. We can now start eyeing on the kingside to create an early attack. There is an important point to address here: throughout the course, I have tried to maintain a certain style or setup that helps us remember the moves better, but in this scenario - there is a difference that needs to be addressed. } { The difference between ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Qc7 8.Bb3 b5 and 7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 ( the other main line chapter [/variation/42468986/#/8/b]). } { - In the case where ...Qc7 is included, we will be going for f3 and g4 or g4 directly, delaying the a2-a3 push. } { - And with ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Be7 we will be pushing 9.a3. There are two reasons for this: }{ Firstly, when Black plays ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Qc7 8.Bb3 b5 9.f3 there is always an option of 9...Nc6 which allows us to go 10.Nxc6 Qxc6 11.a4! which saves a crucial tempo.

Secondly, after ` rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p2ppn2/8/2BNP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 7 '  7...Be7 8.Bb3 b5 9.a3 if Black chooses to play 9...Qc7 then there is no need to push f3 and you can simply launch 10.g4! immediately and once again, save time. That being said, I don't think the difference is really noticeable unless your opponent is booked, which I think is very unlikely since Najdorf players usually have much bigger fish to fry. } Nbd7 
9. f3 { We have arrived at the main position of this chapter, and arguably one of the main lines inside this course. The next few moves are going to be vital, so please take a moment and understand the ideas behind them.

Firstly, in almost all cases we will answer to ...b5 with a3 in order to prevent ...b4 and place our bishop to a2. } ( 9.f3 { Secondly, and this is an extension to the first point: it is not recommended to play a3 without ...b5. For example, should Black play } 9...Nc5 { then } 10.a3 { would allow for } 10...Nxb3 11.cxb3 { and note that since the black pawn is on b7 it allows Black to answer Rc1 with ...Qb8. I have tried to avoid this position throughout the whole chapter. } ) { Thirdly, be on the lookout for sacrifices. In specific:

1) Bxe6,

2) Nf5 and

3) Nd5.

In many of the lines - this can be quite dangerous.

Fourthly, your queen's placement matters. In almost all cases if Black's knight is on c5 then Qd2 is better and if the knight is on e5 then Qe2 is better. I will explain this in further detail in a trainable.

Finally, please keep the ideal setup in mind. This is g4-g5, Qd2 or Qe2, O-O-O, a3, and Ba2. If we are able to achieve this, the setup is successful. } ( 9.Bxe6 $5 { From a practical point of view, I see this as an alternative, especially in faster formats. However, I could not justify this in front of a computer - hence, I have made it clickable. } 9...fxe6 10.Nxe6 { The reason is that Black now has to find } 10...Qb8! { , which I feel is not easy in an actual game. This move is the reason why I did not make Bxe6 an alternative. However, the arising line is still equal. } ( 10...Qa5 { Can be met with } 11.Nxf8! Nxf8 12.Qxd6 { White now has three pawns for a piece and a fantastic compensation. I feel that there is only one move that should be addressed here: } { Nxe4 $5 13.Qd5! Qxd5 14.Nxd5 Ne6 15.Nb6 Rb8 16.O-O-O⩲ And Black still has a lot of problems to solve. } ) ( 10...Qc6 11.Nd5! $16 { Seems horrible for Black. } ) ( 10...Qc4 { Is similar to 10...Qa5. } 11.Nxf8 Rxf8 12.Qxd6 Kf7 13.Bd4 $14 { With O-O-O to follow. White has more than enough compensation for the piece. } ) 11.Qd4 { Preparing to castle and attack the d6-pawn. } ( 11.f4 $5 { Can also be investigated further. } ) 11...Ne5 12.Nxf8 Rxf8 13.O-O-O $10 { And White will eventually take on d6 which will equalise matters. } { 11...Kf7? Lands in serious trouble once again. 12.Ng5+! Since 12...Kg8 is not possible because of 13.Qc4+ . } ) Nc5 
10. g4 $5  Be7 
11. Qd2 O-O 
12. g5 Nfd7 
13. O-O-O b5 
14. a3 { Preventing ...b4 ideas. } Rb8 
15. Kb1 Ne5 ( 15...Nb6 { I have seen a few strong players go for this move instead of ...Ne5, although, not in this exact position. I would like to point out that placing the knight here does not allow for ...b4 anymore. And White can continue with } 16.h4 { And I feel that eventually Black will play ...Nc4 which will transpose. } ) ( 15...b4 $4 { This does not work anymore because of } 16.axb4 Rxb4 17.Nd5! $18 { And now Black is forced to lose material. } ) 
16. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gg5g6,Ga2g8,Gd1g1,Gh5h6][%csl Re6,Rf7,Gg1,Rg6,Rg8,Gh1,Rh6]} { I consider this to be one of the main positions inside the course. This is because we are dealing with one of the few occurances where both sides have achieved their setup successfully, although in our case we did not play Ba2 which probably does not help in this scenario as we need to keep the b2-pawn protected for when Black breaks with ...b4.

There are many choices here for Black but there is only one that does not lead to a worse position. Before dealing with Black's response, let's understand our plan.

We would like to push h5 followed by g5-g6 and finally h6. Pushing g6 or h6 depends on the position we get, but I will say that in 90% of the cases g6 is a better move. This connects with the entire idea behind Sozin since we wish to not just open the g- and h-files but also to weaken the e6-pawn and bring our Sozin bishop into the attack.

Secondly, we wish to push f3-f4 as well but you should keep in mind that Black does have a resource with ...Rd8 where the knight does not move at all. So if this can be avoided, it can be quite dangerous. The idea behind f3-f4 is that after ...Nc4, Bxc4-bxc4, you can play a safe move such as Ka1! and aim to protect the b2-pawn via Rb1. This way any queenside attack is blocked and White basically gets a free hand to develop play on the other side of the board. } Qb7! {[%cal Rb5b4][%csl Rb4,Rb7]} { The best move for Black. There are two reasons to play this:

1) Black's queen is no longer placed on the c7-square which avoids any Nf5-Nd5 ideas and

2) the plan is to push ...b4 and recapture with the queen.

} ( { A) } 16...b4? { Is of course a mistake because of } 17.axb4 Rxb4 18.Nd5! $16 { And we win the exchange. } ) ( { B) } 16...Nc4 17.Bxc4 bxc4 18.Ka1 $16 { As mentioned in my note earlier, White now has a free hand to develop the attack on the kingside. } ) ( { C) } 16...Nxb3 $6 { Just gives us what we want. } 17.cxb3 $14 { And once again our queenside is completely protected. We can launch the attack via f4-h5-g6 or h6. } ) 
17. h5 { We march forward! } b4 { The only logical follow-up as anything else would waste precious time. There are two ways to continue here: and I am honestly not sure which one is better. } ( 17...b4 { A) } 18.axb4 { . } ( { B) } 18.Nd5 $5 { . } ) { I feel both of them are extremely dangerous for Black and the decision of which one is better is a matter of personal taste. I will explain further in the trainable. } ) 
18. axb4 ( { I would like to explain why I chose this as my main move over } 18.Nd5 { as it was something I was confused with for quite sometime. I think both moves have their purpose and you as a player should keep both moves in your arsenal.

However, I chose } ) ( 18.axb4 { because it did not involve any repetition at the end of the variation. Again, I will state that } ) ( 18.Nd5 { is a fantastic alternative and it should be tried in a game if given the opportunity. } ) Qxb4 
19. Qg2 $5  { Bringing the queen in the attack. Right now, the threat of g5-g6 or f3-f4 is quite strong. I think this is a good place to stop for majority of readers as we have been in new territory for a long time and the chances of this happening in a game is quite less. } ( 19.g6 $5 { Can also be investigated further. } ) Nxb3 
20. cxb3 Bd7 {[%csl Gc6]} { Protecting the c6-square. } 
21. g6! ( 21.f4 { Another interesting try that can be investigated further. I only dislike this move because of } 21...Nc4 $5 { But the position is quite interesting for both sides after } 22.Rh3 $13 { Taking on e3 is bad for Black. Black has to find } 22...Na3+ 23.bxa3 Qxc3 { and then after } 24.Bc1 { the position is balanced, but I think the attack is very much alive. } ) h6 { Only move! } 
22. Bxh6 {[%mdl 32768]} { At this point - this should be expected. } gxh6 
23. f4! {[%csl Re5]} { Expanding on the kingside and moving Black's most active piece. } f6? { Black uses the g-pawn as a shield and invites us to take on e5. } 
24. f5 $18  { Beautiful move. Denying the piece and focusing on the big picture. By removing the e6-pawn we can play Nd5 and simply dominate. White is completely winning here. } *

