1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. Bc4 g6 { The infamous 'Dragadorf' variation. The Dragadorf is a hybrid setup of two theoretical giants: Dragon & Najdorf. This variation came into fashion in the early 2010s with a mission to divert mainstream theory and confuse players due to its unique approach toward opening theory. The setup looks weird at first, and that's the gimmick.

Logically speaking, we should assume that Black will not be going for the Dragon setup with ...Bg7; ...O-O; ...Nc6 since the move ...a6 is now a waste of a crucial tempo in an opening that has a reputation for being extremely sharp. We will focus on ...h5 setups instead where the position remains complex and largely unexplored. } 
7. f3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { I believe } 7.Be3 { is pretty similar and will transpose in the next move. } ) Bg7 ( 7...h5 { A bit too soon. White has not yet committed Be3 and can use this opportunity to place the bishop on a better square. } 8.Bg5 $5 Bg7 9.Qd2 $16 { This is an important moment to understand the difference between the Be3 and Bg5. We are simply not allowing Black to opt for the Dragadorf setup. For example, if Black plays } 9...b5 { , we can answer with } 10.Bd5! { and now taking } 10...Nxd5 { is not possible because after } 11.Nxd5 { the e7-pawn is left hanging. } ) 
8. Be3 O-O $6  { As mentioned earlier, this is not in the spirit of the Dragadorf since Black is now simply playing a Dragon with ...a6 - losing a crucial tempo. For example: } 
9. Qd2 b5 
10. Bb3 Bb7 { A logical follow-up. However, leaving the c8-h3 diagonal leaves Black vulnerable on the kingside. } 
11. h4 { Ready to throw h5 if given the opportunity. } h5 
12. g4! hxg4 
13. h5! { Thematic idea inside Dragon - Black is now completely lost. } Nxh5 
14. fxg4 Nf6 
15. Bh6 $18  { With a mating attack. } *

