Logically speaking, we should assume that Black will not be going for the Dragon setup with ...Bg7; ...O-O; ...Nc6 since the move ...a6 is now a waste of a crucial tempo in an opening that has a reputation for being extremely sharp. We will focus on ...h5 setups instead where the position remains complex and largely unexplored. } 
7. f3 ( { I believe } 7.Be3 { is pretty similar and will transpose in the next move. } ) Bg7 ( 7...h5 { A bit too soon. White has not yet committed Be3 and can use this opportunity to place the bishop on a better square. } 8.Bg5 $5 Bg7 9.Qd2 $16 { This is an important moment to understand the difference between the Be3 and Bg5. We are simply not allowing Black to opt for the Dragadorf setup. For example, if Black plays } 9...b5 { , we can answer with } 10.Bd5! { and now taking } 10...Nxd5 { is not possible because after } 11.Nxd5 { the e7-pawn is left hanging. } ) 
8. Be3 Nbd7 $5  { This is where the confusion begins.

Black already deviates from the usual c6-square that isn't viable anymore. With the knight on d7, Black aims to create a setup with ...b5;...Bb7;...Rc8 while holding the king on e8 until the queenside fully develops.

To someone who faces this setup for the first time, it feels strange that Black on purpose is avoiding to castle, so the rational player would try to launch an assault on the king. This is partially wrong. I will elaborate on this a bit later. } 
9. Qd2 b5 
10. Bb3 Bb7 { The most popular move. As mentioned in my previous note, here White can castle on the queenside as the bishop on b7 is not ideally placed for queenside attacking chances. } 
11. O-O-O h5 { It is worth noting that we have transposed into the mainstream Dragadorf setup. For further reference, the move order is: ` rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1 '  1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 g6 6.Be3 Bg7 7.f3 a6 8.Qd2 Nbd7 9.Bc4 b5 10.Bb3 h5 11.O-O-O Bb7 . This position is important to understand rather than theorize. Let's first address what Black is trying to achieve amidst all the mess.

Looking at Black's last move and the fact that Black has not castled yet, it is clear that Black does not want the conventional Yugoslav Attack with g4-h4-h5. This could create confusion in White's mind as in such positions we are almost wired to stare at the kingside.

On the other side of the board, Black's next few moves are logical and easy to make. For example: ...Rc8 and ...Ne5-c4 which would force Bxc4-Rxc4 after which Black can play ...Qc7 and only then castle. This would allow Black to gain a few crucial tempos and develop a queenside attack that is much faster in comparison.

Keeping the above in mind, let's discuss White's plan. Firstly, it is vital to let go of the g2-g4 breakthrough until Black has castled. We should be patient and make moves that target the center, to be more specific, the e-file. This can be done in two ways:

1) either searching for a potential e5-break or

2) Playing Nd5 which provokes ...Nxd5-exd5. If Black does not take on d5, then we can put further pressure on the f6-knight by going Bg5, this would also allow for a potential e5-breakthrough if Black is persistent about not taking on d5.

I recommend starting with 12.Rhe1 first, since it keeps both options open. Another reason for playing this move is that it creates an x-ray along the e-file targeting the king, creating the need for castling on the kingside. } 
12. Rhe1! {[%cal Ge1e8][%csl Ge8]} Rc8 {[%cal Rc8c1][%csl Rc1]} { Black follows the same idea. } ( 12...Ne5 { is also possible. However after } 13.Bg5 Rc8 14.Kb1 { The position transposes [/variation/42104498/#/14/w] into the mainline with ` r2qk2r/1b1nppb1/p2p1np1/1p5p/3NP3/1BN1BP2/PPPQ2PP/2KRR3 b kq - 1 12 '  12...Rc8 . } ) 
13. Kb1 { Safe and sound. } Ne5 { This move feels the most interesting to me. Black continues the plan of ...Nc4. } 
14. Bg5 {[%cal Gf3f4,Ge4e5]} { Once again, keeping the option of e4-e5 alive. In this case, retreating to f2 would not make much sense since the black queen is on d8 as opposed to b6. } Nc4 
15. Bxc4 Rxc4 
16. e5! dxe5 
17. Ne6 {[%mdl 32768]} { The point. } Qxd2 
18. Nxg7+ Kf8 
19. Ne6+ fxe6 
20. Rxd2 $16  {[%csl Re5,Re6,Re7]} { Black is a pawn up at the moment, but the triplets on the e-file more than compensate for this. } *

