7. Be3 Nc6 { The Najdorf-Classical Hybrid.

This variation never really became mainstream from the Najdorf move order, but was fairly popular from the Classical move order. Players like Kasparov, Grischuk, and Svidler have employed it once or twice, but never regularly.

My understanding is that this makes a pretty good weapon for Black against lower-rated players since the mainline is extremely sharp with both kings castling on opposite sides and it is a race against time to mate the king. Generally speaking, Black wants to play ...Be7, ...O-O, ...Qc7, ...b5, and ...Bb7. One benefit of this variation is the element of surprise. } { I have played ` rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6 '  6.Bc4 since I was very young and have around 40 classical games in the database and probably a lot more in faster formats but I never paid any particular attention to this variation since this contributes to a lot of extra theory Black has to memorise on top of Najdorf itself, which is arguably one of the most heavily analyzed variations in chess. } 
8. Bb3 {[%mdl 32768]} { Black now has three serious alternatives. } ( 8.Bb3 { A) } 8...Be7 {

B) } ( 8...Qc7 {

C) } ) ( 8...Na5 { . } ) ) ( 8.Bb3 { A) } 8...Be7 { is the most popular answer here. We will go for a fairly new approach with } 9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.g4 { with ideas of Be3, g5, Qd2, h4 and eventually O-O-O. Once again we see the importance of the Sozin bishop who plays a vital defensive role on the queenside. } ) ( 8.Bb3 { B) } 8...Qc7 { is the second most popular move. We will once again go for the rare } 9.Nxc6 Qxc6 { ( 9...bxc6 would result in a similar position after ` r1b1kb1r/1pq2ppp/p1nppn2/8/3NP3/1BN1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 4 9 '  9.g4 and I fail to see the benefit of having the queen on c7 as opposed to ...Be7) ` r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1qppn2/8/4P3/1BN1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 10 '  10.Qd3⁉ and now Black is simply not in time to develop his king because of threats like Ba4. We will analyse this a bit deeper in a trainable. [/variation/42324361/#/10/w] } ) ( 8.Bb3 { C) } 8...Na5 { is the third most popular move and perhaps the most challenging one since it avoids the entire idea of going Nxc6. Here I recommend } 9.f4 $5 { with ideas of going 10.g4 or 10.f5, in some cases White can also throw e4-e5 which can be quite dangerous. Black has to be precise here and play } 9...Qc7 10.f5 Nxb3 11.cxb3 { with ideas of Rc1 prove to be quite challenging for Black. } ) Be7 { The most popular move. } 
9. Nxc6 bxc6 
10. g4 { Launching the attack on the kingside. Our plan is simple - push g5 followed by Qd2 to protect the pawn with the intention of castling, and the continue the attack via h4-h5. } O-O $6  { This is maybe the most obvious (and naive) choice for Black. Let's dance. } 
11. g5 Nd7 
12. Qd2! {[%csl Gg5]} { The point behind delaying g5 by one move. Black is in big trouble now. } a5 
13. O-O-O Nc5 {[%cal Ra5a4]} { Threatening ...a4. } ( 13...Ne5 { Does not achieve much because of } 14.Na4 ( { It is also possible to play } 14.f4 { where after } 14...a4 { we will exchange everything and go into an endgame via } 15.fxe5 axb3 16.cxb3 dxe5 17.Qxd8 Bxd8 18.Rhg1! { White maintains an enormous advantage because of the queenside structure which cannot be stopped whereas Black's majority on the kingside is stuck because of White's pawn on g5. } ) 14...c5 15.f4 Nc6 16.h4 $18 { And White continues with the attack as usual. For example, } 16...Ba6 17.h5 c4 18.Bxc4 Bxc4 { 17.h6 g6 18.Qc3 and White retains an extra pawn. Any other idea might even be slower for Back. } ) 
14. Bxc5 dxc5 
15. Qe3 Qc7 
16. Na4 ( 16.Na4 16...Ba6 17.c4 $14 ) *

