13... Rc8? {[%mdl 32768]} 
14. Nxe6! { This position happened in a Titled Tuesday match between Ehlvest, J (2528) vs Drygalov, S (2547). The original position deviates from Chapter 1 [/variation/42449485/#/13/w] where instead of 13.g4, White played a slightly inferior move 13.Kb1. In principle, this move is quite logical - but Black has to act fast with ` r2q1rk1/1b2bppp/p2ppn2/np6/3NP3/PBN1BP2/1PP1Q1PP/1K1R3R b - - 0 13 '  13...d5 in order to gain the edge.

Black did not find this and developed with 13...Rc8? instead. Why is this a mistake? White to play. } ( { In the game, White went for } 14.e5 Nxb3 15.Nxb3? Nd5 $17 { And now White can't really sacrifice on d5 since Black has castled and fully developed at the moment - Black went on to win the game. } ) ( { If you are wondering why taking with the bishop is worse, you are not alone. Let's go a bit deeper: } 14.Bxe6 $6 fxe6 15.Nxe6 Qe8 16.Nxf8 Bxf8 { When everything is exchanged, the position becomes more clear. Black's rook on c8 is now a much more active piece in comparison to the rook on f8. I also feel that ...Rxc3 is a very dangerous threat that should not be underestimated. This is why Nxe6 is a better move. } ) fxe6 
15. Bxe6+ Kh8 
16. Bxc8 Qxc8 { Black has to capture with the queen in order to escape the threat of e5. The following move is not easy to find over the board, but knowing this idea can be useful. I think that majority of players (in faster formats, at least) would consider 17.Bd4 as their main candidate move. This would give up your advatage as it allows the knight to sit actively on the c4 square. } 
17. Bc1 $16  {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Ra5c4][%csl Gb2,Gc3,Rc4]} ( 17.Bc1 { This retreat seems strange at first, and the idea should be understood. We are firstly not allowing Black to play } 17...Nc4 18.b3! Ne5 19.Bb2 { where White retains a comfortable edge as the knight is no longer on the active square and our bishop has found it's way to the a1-h8 diagonal. } ) ( 17.Bc1 { Secondly, if Black chooses to do nothing - we can plan } 17...-- 18.Qe1 { or } ( 18.Rd3 { protecting the c3-square and then go for b3-Bb2. I think there are still complications, but White should have the upper hand here. } ) ) 0-1

